The agent and the deeper insights variants.

The agent runs inside an instance, or an on-premises host, and ships what the hypervisor can't see: in-operating-system memory usage, swap, disk space, and filesystem-level disk activity, plus the log files the operating system and applications write. Its configuration is a document often stored in the parameter store and pulled at startup, and the instance's role needs the agent's managed policy.

The agent is the answer to two common scenarios: an instance ran out of memory and nobody noticed, so you install the agent, push memory metrics, and alarm on them; and we need application logs centralized, so you point the agent at the log files and it streams them into log groups.

Two deeper variants are worth knowing. Container insights gives enhanced metrics and logs for the container services, per-container processor, memory, network, and disk, plus container output collected to log groups, enabled once per cluster. And function insights gives function-level diagnostics, cold-start counts, initialization duration, memory curves, and processor time per invocation, delivered as a layer added to the function; the standard function metrics work without it, and this is the deeper view when those aren't enough.
